Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A mad institution where young people are supposed to meet today.
A tomb chapel where the S-Bahn tunnel is now being dug.
Farmers cultivate the former land of farmers.
Munich’s oldest official map promotes exciting stories.
It's annoying when maps are not up-to-date.
Everyone knows this, who has had to get upset, because the car navigation instead of a bypass indicated a green meadow.
The historical maps of the digital Bavaria Atlas, an offer of the state government’s geoportal Bavaria, are anything but current – but that is precisely why they are very revealing.
Especially when compared to current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities have changed in the distribution area of the Munich Mercury since the 19th century.
The digital Bavaria Atlas is a patchwork that is not immediately recognizable.
More detailed maps for cities and municipalities, so-called original position sheets, were incorporated into the large overview map.
According to the Bavarian Surveying Administration, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and originated from the first surveying of Bavaria.
Its owner: Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical recording of Bavaria - for military purposes, of course.
Even though the French troops finally departed with the Peace of Lunéville on February 9, 1801, it was today’s neighbors who created the idea of a comprehensive Bavarian map.
Elector Max IV Joseph continued the project, founding the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates back to 1856 and, like all others, can be found on the website of the Bavarian State Library.
The comparison Former/Today is the most impressive example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which appears in the map of 1856 still relatively isolated.
Sendling was incorporated 21 years after the creation of the map, i.e. in 1877, as a Munich district.
Today, Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
The Untersendling houses are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstraße, which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasant uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where the Westpark is today, you see nothing but fields - at first glance: When zooming in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: handwritten numbered floor pieces from the so-called "overtake", from which the property tax was derived.
Today, small plots no longer occupy farmers there - but small farmers of the plant "Land in Sonne".
A large green area stands out north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, the site of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was in fact still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt you can read in the area of today's district of Au-Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "Auf der Luften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße people were once imprisoned with delusions.
There, in 1858/59, the Munich County Irrenanstalt "Auf der Auer Lüften" was created.
From 1872 onwards, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - that psychiatrist who was brought in connection with the death of King Louis II.
"He was progressive for his time and ended, for example, the chaining of the so-called madmen.
In addition, he has prohibited the staff from using violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, head of the Haidhausen Museum, who has been involved with the institution for an exhibition.
At first, there was room for 280 patients, and later it was expanded to 500 seats.
At some point, this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinik München-Ost has been located there, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany.
On the site of the former Auer Anstalt, young people now meet in the Salesianum in Munich.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth shelter with training facilities.
To the west lies the football field of TSV Munich Ost, east of residential houses from the 1980s.
In 2015, the Children's House "Casa Don Bosco" was erected in an architectural way based on the original building of the madhouse, which had been destroyed during the Second World War during bomb attacks.
The Marienplatz was listed as "Hauptplatz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change to the heart of Munich.
The bombs of the Allies ripped many holes into the city center in December 1944.
One big one remained until today - at the Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business buildings and a burial chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at the Marienhof, where these days the preparatory work is being carried out and on 5 April 2017 the groundbreaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn line takes place.
With the slider you can compare the old Munich map with the aerial view of today - and fill up the hole at the Marienhof.
Civil rights group releases travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri due to the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
“The NAACP Travel Advisory for the state of Missouri, which is due to come into force on August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling through the state, as a number of questionable, race-based incidents have recently occurred across the state and are noted here,” the group said in a statement.
A recent Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as state law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
“They have civil rights violations that happen to people.
They are being stopped because of their skin color, they are being beaten or killed,” said the president of the Missouri NAACP, Rod Chapel, the Kansas City Star.
“We hear complaints at such a frequency that we haven’t heard yet.”
It is the first such warning issued by the organization for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances early in the year after he had no more gasoline while traveling through the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being accused of a crime.
The council also points to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office showing that black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
“The recommendation is that people are aware and inform their families, friends and employees about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be ready whether they bring bail money or let their relatives know they’re traveling through the state.”
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, which ranks the state 16th in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but lately stakeholders have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
