Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now Trump’s White House takes over the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of a regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
The Americans appreciate this as much as any other - hence the carefully staged fall of Saddam Hussein in 2003 in Firdos Square in Baghdad.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump regime’s key ideologues, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated dispute with CNN’s Jim Acosta about the president’s proposals to drastically curb legal immigration.
To remain fair, Miller did not attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had.
But he attacked its meaning, and in particular the meaning attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller told Acosta, “I don’t want to go into a complete thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are referring to, which was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.”
Miller is factually correct, but as he himself put it, it’s not really about history.
It’s about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state invites not only some old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: “Your weary, your poor, / your oppressed masses who yearn to breathe freely, / the miserable waste of your rich coasts.”
There has never been a time when the “miserable garbage” could be seen better on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism – he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump’s USA.
This conflict because of the importance of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural controversy: it is indeed a conflict about the importance of America.
Lazarus - and her friends, who were committed to putting their words at the base after her death - knew very well that they were doing a high-political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting, in a worn-out classical pictorial representation, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed this meaning: In her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The connection of the poem with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people of the right wing wanted to change this back for a long time.
Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative who brings the American flame to the enveloped world: “Lady Liberty is moving ahead.
It is supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch should not illuminate the way to the United States.”
Quite unusually, Limbaugh has come across something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see her as she was seen by the exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
In the truest sense, it is about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome that they need to hear.
And of course, this is not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever want to recognize.
Their torch should not illuminate the way, but ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
