Blocking Critics on Facebook: Don’t Apply for a Public Office if you can’t tolerate electoral heating
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn’t long before the newspapers beat him for everything, from domestic politics to his political principles.
He complained about the criticism, of course.
But he did not silence his critics.
In 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we are led to slaughter like the sheep."
This brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan, who has to work to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s employees have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor’s staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online commentary was full of a counter-reaction with “Well, what?”
“It’s just Facebook,” many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state that is astonishingly popular.
He has the second highest approval of the nation’s 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary heathead.
He has shown a firm hand in the leadership of his state and strict adherence to the principles.
He was also very skilled at using Facebook as a primary means to connect with his voters and playfully debut his hairless head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the side of the governor – which is a public forum called official and from employees paid with public tax dollars – is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan’s spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than a moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people swinging the whip online.
The post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not profane.
The priest quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan’s Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she asked about hate crimes.
“I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no reaction to hate crimes and other current news,” she wrote in the comments section of The Post.
"I don't appreciate this idea either, if a number of people take a position on the same issue, then they are disregarded by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of affected citizens."
What the governor’s staff called a “concentrated spam attack” would likely be called “pronunciation.”
The Facebook era makes it easy to crop a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It’s much cleaner than in the past if you’d done the same thing that employees were sent out to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or arrest and silence protesters.
But that is exactly what is happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for insulting Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is sued by Twitter users who have been blocked by his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones in this matter fell last week in Virginia.
Loudoun County’s Chairman of the Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
At the time of Washington, the time of affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letterwriters responded to his leadership.
Even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people who used pseudonyms like "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius" and "Portius" wrote all letters to newspapers that defeated Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on Amity’s treaty, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected from the George Washington Project’s online papers.
But he didn't silence her.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
True leadership means accepting it.
