Poverty and death in Indonesian Goldland
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually places a sweet potato - locally referred to as "nota" - directly in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and swallowed with zealous, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing clothes with cloudy water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink heavy, and there are the soldiers here.
“No one dares walk around the village after 5 p.m.,” she says.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated in Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum, when only 1,026 elders were supposed to vote by a public hand raise before the occupation forces.
An existing movement that pushed for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control of the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers from doing so.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea encompassing the eastern part of the island.
The journey includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and then a morning 5-hour drive by car.
There is no public transport.
The city with about 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, and corrugated roofs that have been converted into various yellowish tones by rust.
Very few Indonesians have made their trip here, let alone journalists and practically no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuan worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes, too.
“We weren’t used to wearing those clothes,” says Degei, pointing to her vivid, hand-woven turban, dark shirt, and light skirt.
“We used to have only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia’s Goldland.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran from Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion worth of wood resources.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuan people, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 study in the New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua’s tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide, according to the Asia Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
“We Will Lose Everything,” says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities of the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture – rape and electric strikes are particularly popular, according to another report – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s difficult to count the number of casualties as incidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia’s researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have strengthened as Papua’s resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The population of 3.5 million inhabitants of the province is 83% Christian, but demographic development is changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warning canteens sell fried chicken and gadado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting to keep up.
“Migrants have started selling chickens and vegetables on the traditional market cheaper than the local Papua,” explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura.
"It cost the native Papua - the mother-mother [the women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised to address inequalities and violations in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of the 29 districts of Papua - including Paniai - on his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokovi in 2014, with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes that justice will be restored,” You said.
In fact, Paniai suffered a low just two months after Jokovi’s inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children was out singing Christmas songs in front of a campfire in Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offense at her tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers who had drunk hunted and beat the group with their rifle pistons, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
A child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so severely beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
Approximately 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting arches and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird song - of Papua's Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters started throwing stones at police and military posts.
When the mood was heated, the soldiers were sent a command via an internal radio: “If the masses resist more than three times, they shoot them dead,” according to an official document from TIME that was not released to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, saw the impending danger and called for peace and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot into my left wrist," he said TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
“It was crowded, many shots were fired,” he adds.
The native man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shootings.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” said Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, carries only one name, the TIME in a gloomy mood.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papuan police chief inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers only wanted to “secure” her station because she was being attacked.
“We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said Papuan police spokesman, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, in 2015.
“It’s about life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
The news of the killings did not come to Jakarta until the next day.
For three weeks, Jokovi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the historical misfortunes in Papua.
“I want this case to be resolved immediately, so it won’t happen again in the future,” he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he was setting up an out-of-court mechanism to settle historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
“Most injuries occurred a long time ago.
Some were in the 90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we have committed to addressing these violations, but there are processes that need to be gone through,” he said.
Then Wiranto made a retreat when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on June 5 and said he had no plans to set up a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, “everything is regulated by law,” he said.
Wiranto, whom the UN has accused of “crimes against humanity,” which claimed more than 1,000 deaths in East Timor’s bloody independence vote of 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
Families of the Paniai victims accepted such claims with grim disbelief.
“I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there has been no progress,” Yohanes says.
"I'm tired."
He says he still lives in fear years later.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid to be arrested by the military, I’m afraid to be shot.”
His brother Yacobus repeated the view that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four of the victims.
“After I buried the bodies, the military was looking for me,” he says.
The shootings did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Paniai’s neighborhood Deiyai.
During a confrontation between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to take an unconscious man to the hospital, one person died and 17 others were injured, including children.
The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Excited villagers protested in front of the company’s location office.
Police said the villagers threw stones at officers who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting at the crowd and killed one.
“We were so panicked, we’re afraid there will be revenge,” says 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed how the injured were quickly admitted here, according to TIME.
“I hid in my house for two days.”
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the officers involved to be held accountable and the mobile brigade of the police to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been an turmoil for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development strengthens the dissatisfaction of the tribes of Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal, who live in the green highlands of Papua.
Many joined the “Free Papua Movement” (OPM), the rebel army that claims to defend the rights of Papua by instigating sporadic attacks and abductions of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders are from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained in Paniai in recent years, under the pretext of "securing national sovereignty".
Some never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as “a tragic, forgotten place.”
Poverty strengthens dissatisfaction.
The bit of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is also out of reach.
People here grow everything they eat: notes and fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the task of the women, who can each process four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They keep the majority of the harvest for the family, while the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten notes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities between the native Papuan and the new migrants have increased since the opening of new flight routes to Nabire Airport.
The few jobs that exist in the region usually go to the more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papua rarely has the capital or skills to run its own businesses competitively.
“The young people are not interested in staying in the village ... because there are no jobs or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps the world’s eyes away from Papua.
In addition, restrictions on international media coverage remain tense.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for lack of coordination with related institutions, despite being given rare permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, Deputy Asia Director of Human Rights Watch, Jokowi’s campaign promises to lift the restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development have not been realized.
“There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to report from Indonesia’s most troubled eastern provinces of Papua and Western Papua: visa denial and a blacklist,” he said in a statement.
Lack of press control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government remains largely limited to the immediate neighbors of Papua.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands – called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate the “different and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have historically supported OPM.
