Ancient maps from around 1600 underpin this historical situation.
The patronage law originated from early medieval church law.
A gentleman who built a church, equipped it and occupied it with a pastor, remained the owner of the church and was able to inherit it.
This was accompanied by the right to appoint a pastor or to propose a new pastor to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
