“We want law enforcement, we want ending, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
“We cannot come to healing and reconciliation until we receive justice.”
A court doctor lays a bedclothe over the body of one of the victims of the Moore-Ford-Lynchen on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files received from NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and the surrounding counties were suspected in the lynching process.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have remained free for decades, civil rights activists say the double motivation for the Lynch actions has always been known throughout the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a decision of the Supreme Court allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in the pre-election campaign in the summer.
About the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black farm farmer Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight – allegedly because of a woman.
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hester had slept with Malcom’s wife, Dorothy, and that the baby she wore wasn’t from her husband.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to free Malcom from prison, according to the FBI.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they moved away from the prison and approached Moore’s Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
“It turns out it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the murders,” an FBI report concluded.
