New results of Swedish asylum age assessment tests published
Recent results from tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have undergone a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80 percent of the subjects tested are over 18 years of age. But not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish authority for forensic medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) has started to conduct the tests last year.
They should make the assessment of age more accurate during the asylum procedure after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were assessed as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was “possibly 18 years of age or older.”
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person “possibly under 18 years of age.”
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent in recent months.
“We don’t see a big difference in the statistics of the past few months, the numbers are pretty constant,” he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases in which the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases that “suggest that the person examined was 18 years of age or older.”
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of these cases, the person had openly stated that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI shots of knee joints are taken, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing people’s biological maturity to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think the type of measurement should be used.
Evaluating biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can’t say it for sure, we shouldn’t pretend we could,” he told Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: “In general, you can say that the risk of judging a child incorrectly as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is if the person is just under 18, in this case that’s about 10 percent.”
