How Football’s Financial Rules Affect Neymar’s Moving to Paris
The rules aimed at preventing unhindered spending on European football clubs will not interfere with Neymar’s world record transfer from Spain’s Barcelona to France’s Paris-Saint Germain.
Any consequences for Paris Saint-Germain will still come from UEFA, as the leading organization that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from accessing the prestigious Champions League tournament.
Financial fair play rules launched by UEFA in 2011 mean that PSG will have to prove at some point that the transfer of Neymar was funded without major losses.
Barcelona has paid 222 million euros ($262 million) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will amount to several tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar’s move to France.
PSG can certainly loosen the money for Neymar to sign and take him to a galaxy of other stars, given the team’s funding from the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on acquiring players, but must counteract with legitimate sources of income that allow them to break-even point in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA President in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had taken on enormous debt in their pursuit of success effectively cheated and risked ruining themselves when banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from focusing on clubs’ debt to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used in Chelsea in 2003 – buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the team and build a global brand – was to become a tougher affair.
During the current three-year FFP predisposition period, which runs until 2018, clubs can accept losses of 30 million euros.
And despite Platini’s disgrace from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin continues to work to deter excessive spending.
"Surely, FFP is not dead and we will strengthen the rules for the future," Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the buy-out clause of Neymar in a lump sum, it can distribute the amount for the accounting over the duration of its contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so that the transfer amount of 44.4 million euros can be reported in the annual financial statements for the next five years.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, along with Abu Dhabi owned by Manchester City, has hit PSG with the most severe sanctions.
The PSG received a fine of €60 million (then $82 million), which was later reduced to €20 million - and it was ordered that the team members for the 2014/15 Champions League be limited to 21 players instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA is looking for clubs that could try to outsmart their financial oversight by inflating their revenues through companies associated with the owners of a club.
While a Qatari company could sponsor the PSG if the value of the sponsorship exceeded the standard market rates, UEFA would not consider this a legitimate income.
That’s exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of PSA sponsorship was inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It has been reported that some of the PSG payments to Neymar could come through payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will be a World Cup ambassador and that such a manoeuvre could be easy for UEFA regulators to figure out.
The sanctions against PSG so far mean that UEFA will be even more attentive to every attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA had no preparatory talks with PSG about Neymar’s transfer, said the people familiar with the situation on Thursday.
They spoke with The Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show that PSG 2015/16 generated a profit of more than 10 million euros with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have yet to be published.
PSG expects Neymar’s arrival to be a blessing for sponsorship deals, merchandising and jersey sales.
The association expects sales to increase by at least 30 percent after signing.
The Spanish league was clearly irritated to see one of the best footballers go, and they tried to prevent Neymar’s departure by claiming that PSG would violate the FFP.
"It's a clear case of 'financial doping' with the club and the state," said La Liga President Javier Tebas, the Spanish daily AS regarding Qatar's ultimate ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's reservations against a state that finances a club.
“It’s the consequence of ownership and that has completely changed the entire landscape of football over the past 15 years,” Wenger said.
“As soon as a country has a club, anything is possible.
It will be very difficult to respect financial fair play because you can go different ways or have different interests when a country has such a big player to represent a country.”
