NHS (National Health Service) to Prescribe Controversial HIV Drugs to 10,000 People
Patients will be given access to a “transformative” HIV prevention treatment from September onwards after a fight in front of the High Court against funding the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken prior to sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 percent, is now delivered by the health service through an initial three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the trial after the appeals court confirmed a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS had the authority to pay for the PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was hailed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as an “important new intervention,” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, and more clinics will follow in October before it will be launched across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a sequence of HIV supplements taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that there are just enough drugs in a person’s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medications can be taken every day or so as early as two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and individuals with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics identify appropriate participants who agree to the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also sign up for a possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The program will be worth 10 million pounds and NHS England signed a contract to deliver the drugs this week after an international competitive sourcing.
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is used, absorbed and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: “This great new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in the more than three decades of ongoing progress in addressing one of humanity’s greatest health challenges.”
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted to people in need and at risk, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people at high HIV risk will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement.”
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The priority must now be that the study is conducted quickly across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP test medicine has been procured, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 HIV-infected people.”
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Secretary, said: “The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and hesitant implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and can end the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This attempt brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it’s important that this study is conducted as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are HIV-infected and that it will help us get a step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society.”
