She watched a live feed where a police officer stood in front of a group of demonstrators with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer unlocked his rifle and shouted, “I’m going to kill you... animals all.”
“That’s not common,” Ferrell recalled her statement.
“This isn’t the kind of murder we’ve gotten used to and can be called typical.”
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.”
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided that the two would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the theme of a new documentary film, Whose Streets?, in theaters from the 11th onwards.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience, which consists from the point of view of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell went to Ferguson with her daughter, who wore a floral dress and a matching crown, the two discussed a conversation that they had had countless times before this morning “about the black experience and the black condition.”
“You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?” she recalled what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that wasn't right.
I couldn’t take her with me,” Ferrell said later.
“What happened today is a climax of what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see and be raised in it.
It must be well-developed, knowing not only activism and organization, but also the different layers of black experience and black constitution and what we need to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even though I’m lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn’t personally experience blatant racism, she’s no different from the next black woman child.
I feel like I would do her a disservice to keep her away from it.”
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place opposite the police department that became a camp area when activists were waiting for officer Darren Wilson’s possible non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who made lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to demonstrators.
Slowly a new type of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism changed completely after August 9th," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association, focusing on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I had no experience in organizing.
Everything has come."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell’s mind: “Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story that you can take advantage of?”
This skepticism was nurtured by countless cases of people, often whites - in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently explained in an interview, “We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn’t center their voices and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist in the field known for his activism around death row inmates.
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals, followed the team of Whose Streets in the years following Brown's shooting.
"This documentary isn't someone who speaks for us or speaks to us, we're talking," Davis said.
“That was the main thing for me how these people are portrayed, because that’s how I’ll be portrayed.”
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience – to show that the movement “is not a Messiah leader, but a community coming together,” Folayan said – it proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from “Whose Streets?” surprisingly show personal aspects of Ferrell’s life as she falls in love and marries her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing when she saw the finished product for the first time.
"But I understand that there must be some vulnerability to this work and to the humanization of black people."
In addition, Ferrell’s story reiterates the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives matte movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who coined the movie BlacklivesMatter on social media after the killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify as gay.
“Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement overall,” Ferrell said, “and that’s why we’re constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of everything.”
Folayan agreed to note that “the movement is really being upheld by black women and many black women.”
However, she insists that “this is not an affirmative type of action” where Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
“She was the person who stirred up that energy,” she said.
“It’s not a coincidence, though she was at the forefront, because there’s so much at stake in a life at these crossroads as a black, gay woman.
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, the news cameras in Ferguson have long since disappeared, but the racial ties between the community and the police continue.
Ferrell is on parole for 2 1/2 years for blocking a highway in a demonstration.
She describes the social-political atmosphere of the area she calls her home: “Chaos.”
Still, she clings to a song and feels committed to that memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose except our chains.”
