Funding for the city centre III
If you want to renovate your old house, you can soon get support from the country.
Mayor Albert Schindler and three representatives of STEG Urban Development informed about this on Wednesday in Empfingen.
At the beginning of the information event, Schindler gave a look back at what has happened so far.
Since 1991 there have been rehabilitation areas in Empfingen.
At that time, between 1991 and 2004, the state of Baden-Württemberg had taken over two thirds of the funding.
In Rehabilitation Area II from 2005 to 2016, the grant was still 60 percent.
For Schindler, the previous renovations are a "successful project" - after all, it is important to promote interior development and not only to open up new construction areas.
On April 4th, the Karlsruhe government received the information that there will be a rehabilitation area III.
The funding amounted to 833,333 euros, of which 500 000 euros would come from the country, the rest from the municipality of Empfingen.
How does a rehabilitation area come about?
According to Schindler, it will be investigated where the "really old" houses are.
However, it also plays a role whether there is any interest in refurbishment in the planned area.
If necessary, the territorial boundaries could also be shifted again.
The STEG represented on Wednesday evening Martin Keller, Gaby Pietzschmann and Sarah Gotzel.
Keller presented the contents of the federal-country program "Social City", in which the renovations would then be carried out.
The core of the programme is the revitalisation of inner cities, the improvement of living and working conditions and the preservation and expansion of infrastructure.
The measures would be carried out on an object-related basis, i.e. per plot of land.
The rehabilitation area would then finally be defined as a statute.
The granting period for the grants runs from 1 January 2017 until 30 April 2026.
Until September of this year, however, the inventory would be carried out, within the framework of which the participants in the rehabilitation area would be given a questionnaire to fill out.
If possible, the decision on the statutes should be taken in November or December, so that the renovations can begin in the coming year.
Pietzschmann then stated that each municipality had to carry out the aforementioned preliminary investigations.
It is a matter of assessing the urban deficiencies and deciding when and to what extent they will be refurbished.
A refurbishment note will then be entered in the land register for the respective property.
Pietzschmann himself would come to Empfingen again and get a picture of the situation, she promised.
Gotzel stressed that a key success factor for the project was the participation of the participants.
Therefore, there will be questionnaires that will be sent to the citizens by post in the coming weeks and can be filled in until after the end of the summer holidays.
The yellow questionnaire is the "building and land sheet", which deals, among other things, with the structural condition and the refurbishment intentions.
In the grey questionnaire, the "household and housing sheet", information can be given on the size, division and inhabitants of a living space.
The blue "operating sheet" is only to be completed if business premises are operated in the building.
However, it should be noted that Gotzel pointed out that a completed questionnaire is not at the same time an application for funding.
In addition, new construction measures are not eligible.
Schindler also emphasized that the distribution of funding works according to the "wind dog principle" - who comes first, grinds first.
No funding can be “reserved” for later.
