White House advertising costs thousands of dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a naval helicopter to the South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month cost taxpayers up to $24,000, according to the military, which was left to TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the president is on board was at the heart of the July 17 event at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was exhibited alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a fragmentary order or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to the records of the Navy Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
“I just wanted you to be aware of this because it’s such an unusual event with high visibility,” the HMX-1 commander wrote to his supervisor, the deputy naval commander for aviation, on the eve of the event.
The news indicated that the helicopter arrived at the South Lawn on July 17 around 7 in the morning for the event at 3 p.m., and remained until the lawn was cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. that evening.
The note adds that if the departure from the White House should be delayed, due to the limitation of the hours of service, a second crew would be needed for the return flight.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the security personnel of the unit stayed on the ground with the aircraft during the time.
The records provided to TIME did not clearly show whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event could violate the determination.
“One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case,” the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're locked," replied the deputy commander.
The “Made in America” event was designated by the White House as an official event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But official events also have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave an impetus to the health reform that was underway in the Senate, and he propagated efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for politically beneficial purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are obliged to use them for the trip.
But requesting their use only for a photo-op is uncommon.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was providing taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of reports complaining about his predecessor’s use of the presidential plane.
“The White House is thrilled with the show “Made In America” – which shows products from all 50 states made by American workers using American materials,” White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters said.
HMX-1 crews often conduct training flights in the Washington area and in the South Lawn to drop the White House president with precise centimetre rates.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 exercise landings at the White House.
The flight for the “Made in America” event counted in the flight crew’s training requirements for the month, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for “non-presidential support missions.”
The White House said taxpayers took over the burden for none of the other props presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in exhibiting the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to U.S. Department of Defense hourly rates for the 2017 financial year, the DoD refund rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Records of the unit record the flight time of the aircraft as 30 minutes from the home base of the Marine Corps Air Facility in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far below this rate.
"Determining the cost to taxpayers based on the estimates for the refund rates is highly misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs included in the annual funds."
According to a 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement rates for DoD do not include personnel costs, but take into account the costs of fuel, maintenance and contracting.
At that time, the former White House press spokesman, Sean Spicer, defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase things made in America this week,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contribution to our national security, and I assume that hundreds, if not thousands, of people depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we’re all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly for.
Of course, it is appropriate to emphasize that.”
It wasn’t clear if Trump was interacting with the helicopter when he entered his South Lawn tour for the event, but he sat down in the driver’s seat of a fire truck.
In the White House, Trump spoke to representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president, "I have three of them."
