GMB concerns about investment in McVitie factory in Glasgow
A union wants to make sure to managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie about the long-term commitment to production at their plant in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said the company was silent on the future of tollcross investment.
More than 500 employees work at the factory, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies among other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than 5 million pounds in recent years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would “know first” if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company’s branch manager, GMB Scotland urged McVitie’s to “express concerns that funding for the modernization of production lines will not be pushed forward.”
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy said: “The fact that we cannot gain clarity from the general site manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is strongly focused on the local community and the Greater Glasgow area, an important pillar for decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social disadvantage.
Therefore, in the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising cost of living and the chronic decline in production, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving production presence at McVitie.”
A Pladis spokeswoman said: “The branch manager at Tollcross just received a letter from GMB Scotland yesterday, and the company will respond directly to it as we appreciate the ongoing engagement with employees and trade union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some questions were openly discussed.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our divisions and locations - to remain competitive.
She added: “Over the past few years, we’ve invested more than 5 million pounds in our tollcross site, especially in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognize the legacy of Tollcross as a production site, and should our operations change, the employees and their trade union representatives will be the first to find out."
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar three years ago?
The La Liga side may regret their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain won’t give up in her pursuit of Neymar after she made an offer of 189 million pounds to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona of the world record raid three years ago?
