In connection with the reports of the abuse cases, Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
Completely wrong, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who together with Ratzinger wrote the memory book "My Brother the Pope" (translated into 12 languages).
“I have to protect Georg Ratzinger,” says Hesemann, “because all this had nothing to do with him,” he evaluates the results of the final report.
What exactly is stated in the 440-page report submitted by the lawyer Ulrich Weber, commissioned by the Diocese of Regensburg with the Enlightenment?
A total of 547 Regensburg cathedrals were sexually abused between 1945 and the early 1990s "with high plausibility" victims of assaults, 67 cathedrals were sexually abused.
The final report says about Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994: "In summary, it can be stated that Domkapellmeister R. has used forms of physical and psychological violence in many cases.
Especially with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be more severe.
Nevertheless, unlike many other accused, it is noticeable that many victims valued the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases, despite violence, even associate positive memories with him.
In an interview, Hesemann explains why he believes the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg cathedral sparrows relieves Georg Ratzinger.
Mr. Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "incidents of violence against guardians at the Regensburg Domspatzen" gives a contradictory picture of Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students emphasize his “humanity.”
On the other hand, he also appears as a cholericist and perfectionist, who often became tangible when a Domspatz did not perform top-notch musically.
How do you view this final report as his biographer?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble and read the entire 440-page report from front to back, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger is even found in it.
There are only eight pages dedicated to him and he is clearly acquitted of any suspicion of complicity in the horrible cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of violence in preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
You can at best accuse him of not knowing it too late or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, on which he worked, was perceived by practically all respondents as - so literally - "salvation", "heaven" and "better world".
For example, the vast majority of his students, Georg Ratzinger, also exhibits an excellent testimony, describing him as "warmhearted", "popular", "sincere", "competent" and "compassionate", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, cookies and candies and was "always surrounded by grapes of children".
Only a minority complains about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which has also led to outbursts of anger.
That he not only banged with chairs and threw the keychain on the floor, but also distributed ear figs and pulled too naughty guys on his hair or ears, he himself admitted years ago, deeply regretted and apologized for it.
In his honor, however, it must be said that such methods of education were widespread in the period in question, the 1960s and 1970s, among parents as well as teachers.
Do you know of such methods of discipline?
Of course, I think every one of us who was born before 1968.
I also experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
Compared to what this report is actually about, namely the horrible sexual abuse and the excesses of violence in preschool, these are, of course, bagatelles.
One wonders whether it has to do with his reputation and his role as brother of Benedict XVI that many media have just rushed over to him.
Many people who have never understood the pope are still working hard on the Bavarian pope.
But the truth is: the report relieves Georg Ratzinger in every way!
Much has been reported in the media about the abuse of the Regensburg Domspatzen in connection with the report.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused of any involvement or involvement in sexual abuse in the final report?
Michael Hesemann: Clearly no.
None of the 67 victims of sexual assault claim to have entrusted themselves to the Domkapellmeister.
Not even the parents were involved.
“I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it,” one person said on behalf of the others, “I was all very embarrassed.”
The real problem with elucidating sexual abuse was and still is that most victims are silent out of shame.
If they did not even entrust themselves to parents and siblings, then certainly not to a choirmaster, who would have been a colleague of the perpetrators in a certain professional sense.
How do Domspatzen students rate Ratzinger’s role in the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: An interviewed student put it this way: "As to sexual abuse ... I see ... no case in which, of all things, he (Georg Ratzinger) had timely insights and could have stopped the perpetrator.
I think it ... is also really absurd to assume that ... boys have been more insistent or clear or more open to him than to their parents, boarding directors, trust teachers, etc.
Talking to him about sex is unthinkable.”
The report thus comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that students and/or their surroundings entrusted themselves to him in advance could not be confirmed in the course of the investigation".
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger can therefore be acquitted of any co-awareness.
So he cannot be accused of not having prevented him or brought him to report.
Therefore, there is no reason to associate his good name with these abominable crimes, as unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media there was a lot to read about "Gewaltexzessen" at the Regensburg Domspatzen.
The former Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report "Wegschauen".
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: That is the big problem that in the reporting everything was mixed and mixed into a huge melange of sexual abuse and violence and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that, in turn, is an abuse of the report.
There is a clean separation: between the preschool and the high school of the Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence, and, let’s say, other allegations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the period since 1945, i.e. also from four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not the choral director of the cathedral.
All the horrible beatings, the cases where boys were harassed and misrepresented by sadistic teachers and suffered appallingly, all occurred at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where truly scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he only got to see the boys when they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium.
On this, as most witnesses emphasize, the topic of "preschool" was taboo.
One was just happy to have escaped her and enjoyed the so much better treatment and for many even "paradise" conditions.
What was different at Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was already discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, where the report concludes that "many victims valued the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases, despite violence, even associate positive memories with him".
At the most, the accusation remains to have looked away.
However, despite all the efforts, the report was able to define only two periods in which it was reported on preschool conditions.
The first time in 1970/71, when he just started to establish himself and did not want to hear anything about the events at a school where he was not working and was responsible (so the witness) and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because already in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it, he points out that "in preschool the beating penalty will continue to be practiced".
Already in view of the danger of negative press releases, he recommended urgent intervention.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when beating penalties were long banned in Bavaria.
Before that, they occurred in a legal grey area, as we all know.
It was also difficult for him to estimate where those affected might have been exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can’t say he’d always looked away.
That's just not true.
It was not until 1980 that the beating penalty in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today’s pedagogical standards to the time.
How do you see that?
Michael Hesemann: We historians speak of the “fall-trick of anachronism”, that is, the danger of assessing the past according to today’s moral standards.
The princess is right.
But of course this does not apply to sexual abuse, which has been abhorrent at all times, nor to what was done in preschool in terms of adversity and violence against innocent children’s souls, that goes far beyond what was usual at the time.
It’s all horrible and I’m glad it’s finally being worked up.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of disciplining and punishing, i.e. pulling ear figs and on his hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When physical punishment was then banned, he also strictly adhered to it.
What picture of his Regensburg era did Georg Ratzinger reproduce in the conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Was the issue of punishment also discussed?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, that is Pope Benedict XVI, tells from his perspective that the Domsparts played only a secondary role.
Nevertheless, I do not deny that he led a strict regiment there.
But this must also be said: Without this perfectionism, without the demand of unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form an institution of world-class, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and his musical tradition, who went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and candies alone, you don’t make big singers out of rebellious boys and stand before every success, no matter what field, but always discipline, passion and self-overcoming.
As what kind of person did you experience Georg Ratzinger in the conversations about her book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger very well and have experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, generous, deeply believing and good-hearted person, who you can't imagine could do anything to even a fly.
I regularly get to see how many former catholic sparrows still keep in regular contact with him today, 23 years after his retirement, visiting him, reading to him - he's almost blind - and treating him like a member of her family.
So those who have not forgiven him for being strict with them are clearly in the minority.
Most Domspatzen are grateful to him today for enriching their lives and teaching them the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, for sure, that may be - but he was also a dearly respectful person to whom they still look up today and whom they worship.
And please, again, clearly: all he is accused of is educational methods that were common at the time.
We can be glad that we have overcome this time a long time ago.
But it is highly unjust to turn a man into a media scapegoat just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
The evil intent behind it is all too obvious.
Because the report that has just been published relieves him.
Now the decency would be to leave a 93-year-old man, who has earned great merits and without the outside of Bavaria and perhaps Germany probably no one would know the Regensburg Domspatzen, finally in peace.
